<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="92" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="17.[189,334,365,391]" box="[189,334,365,391]" pageId="17" pageNumber="92">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,334,365,391]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="17" pageNumber="92" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,334,365,391]" pageId="17" pageNumber="92">Description</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[189,1399,412,826]" pageId="17" pageNumber="92">
Shrubs or trees, 
<quantity box="[391,491,412,439]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.75" metricValueMax="8.0" metricValueMin="1.5" pageId="17" pageNumber="92" unit="m" value="4.75" valueMax="8.0" valueMin="1.5">1.5–8 m</quantity>
tall. Leaves chartaceous to coriaceous, petiole 
<quantity box="[1073,1174,412,439]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" metricValueMax="6.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="17" pageNumber="92" unit="mm" value="4.0" valueMax="6.0" valueMin="2.0">2–6 mm</quantity>
long, lamina 4.4– 15.5 × 
<quantity box="[275,412,447,474]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.05" metricValueMax="5.8" metricValueMin="2.3" pageId="17" pageNumber="92" unit="cm" value="4.05" valueMax="5.8" valueMin="2.3">2.3–5.8 cm</quantity>
, narrowly elliptic to elliptic, narrowly ovate or lanceolate to oblanceolate, adaxial surface glabrous and abaxial surface glabrous to glabrescent, base cuneate to acute, apex attenuate to acute, slightly acuminate or obtuse, primary vein impressed adaxially and raised abaxially, 7–12 pairs of secondary veins, angles between primary and secondary veins 40–60°. Inflorescence one-flowered, axillary, supra-axillary, terminal or leaf-opposed, bracts absent. Flowers with pedicel 
<quantity box="[1160,1254,588,615]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" metricValueMax="6.0" metricValueMin="4.0" pageId="17" pageNumber="92" unit="mm" value="5.0" valueMax="6.0" valueMin="4.0">4–6 mm</quantity>
long, flower buds 3–6 × 
<quantity box="[321,418,623,650]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="17" pageNumber="92" unit="mm" value="2.0" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="1.0">1–3 mm</quantity>
, globose to ovoid to conical with acute apex, covered in trichomes. Sepals completely connate, calyx cupuliform, apex truncate to triangular, 3–6 × 
<quantity box="[926,1028,659,685]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" metricValueMax="7.0" metricValueMin="4.0" pageId="17" pageNumber="92" unit="mm" value="5.5" valueMax="7.0" valueMin="4.0">4–7 mm</quantity>
, densely covered in trichomes. Petals linear, white, rarely yellowish, 
<quantity box="[631,728,694,720]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.5" metricValueMax="9.0" metricValueMin="6.0" pageId="17" pageNumber="92" unit="mm" value="7.5" valueMax="9.0" valueMin="6.0">6–9 mm</quantity>
long, covered in trichomes, stamens 3–6, 2–3 × ca 
<quantity box="[1331,1399,694,720]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="17" pageNumber="92" unit="mm" value="1.0">1 mm</quantity>
long, carpels 5–8, 
<quantity box="[403,499,729,755]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="17" pageNumber="92" unit="mm" value="2.5" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="2.0">2–3 mm</quantity>
long. Monocarps 2–5, globose to ellipsoid, 8–13 × 
<quantity box="[1099,1199,729,756]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" metricValueMax="9.0" metricValueMin="5.0" pageId="17" pageNumber="92" unit="mm" value="7.0" valueMax="9.0" valueMin="5.0">5–9 mm</quantity>
, densely covered in trichomes, sessile, calyx caducous. Seeds 3–4, wide obovoid to ellipsoid, 7–7.2 × 
<quantity box="[1188,1260,764,791]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="17" pageNumber="92" unit="mm" value="4.0">4 mm</quantity>
, obovoid to ellipsoid, brownish, rugose, with aril.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="18" lastPageNumber="93" pageId="17" pageNumber="92" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="17.[189,494,864,891]" box="[189,494,864,891]" pageId="17" pageNumber="92">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,494,864,891]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="17" pageNumber="92" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,494,864,891]" pageId="17" pageNumber="92">Distribution and habitat</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[189,1398,911,973]" lastBlockId="18.[189,1398,265,328]" lastPageId="18" lastPageNumber="93" pageId="17" pageNumber="92">
<taxonomicName box="[189,520,911,937]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Annonaceae" genus="Hornschuchia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Magnoliales" pageId="17" pageNumber="92" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="mediterranea">
<emphasis box="[189,520,911,937]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="92">Hornschuchia mediterranea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs inland in 
<collectingRegion box="[722,794,911,937]" country="Brazil" name="Bahia" pageId="17" pageNumber="92">Bahia</collectingRegion>
. It inhabits seasonal semideciduous forest, seasonal deciduous forest and lowland tropical moist forest (
<bibRefCitation author="Gouvea J. B. S. &amp; Mattos Silva L. A. &amp; Hori M." box="[790,1018,946,973]" pageId="17" pageNumber="92" pagination="1 - 7" refId="ref22172" refString="Gouvea J. B. S., Mattos Silva L. A. &amp; Hori M. 1976 1. Fitogeografia. In: Diagnostico socioeconomico da Regiao cacaueira Vol. 7: 1 - 7. Comissao Executiva do Plano da Lavoura Cacaueira and the Instituto Interamericano de Ciencias Agricolas-OEA., Recursos Florestais, Ilheus." type="journal article" year="1976">
Gouvêa 
<emphasis box="[890,949,946,972]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="92">et al.</emphasis>
1976
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Thomas W. W. &amp; Barbosa M. R. V." box="[1029,1326,946,973]" pageId="17" pageNumber="92" pagination="6 - 20" refId="ref24665" refString="Thomas W. W. &amp; Barbosa M. R. V. 2008. Natural vegetation types in the Atlantic Coastal Forest of Northeastern Brazil. In: Thomas W. W. (ed.) The Atlantic Coastal Forest of Northeastern Brazil. Memoirs of the New York Botanical Garden 100: 6 - 20." type="journal article" year="2008">Thomas &amp; Barbosa 2008</bibRefCitation>
), with one occurrence near the Caatinga domain, a xeric vegetation 
<typeStatus box="[911,964,265,291]" pageId="18" pageNumber="93">type</typeStatus>
, in the municipality of Mundo Novo (
<figureCitation box="[197,273,301,328]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="17.[189,231,1963,1989]" captionTargetBox="[189,1395,1069,1924]" captionTargetId="figure-253@17.[189,1398,1069,1924]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="Fig. 5. Geographical distribution of Hornschuchia mediterranea Mello-Silva &amp; D.M.Johnson, H. myrtillus Nees and H. obliqua Maas &amp; Setten. Abbreviations: BA = Bahia; ES = Espírito Santo." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6823780" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6823780/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="93">Figs 5</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[286,326,302,328]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="27.[180,222,1653,1682]" captionTargetBox="[339,1772,544,1595]" captionTargetId="figure-12@27.[339,1774,532,1608]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="Fig. 7. Patterns of distribution, richness, abundance and endemism for Hornschuchia Nees. In green the legal delimitation of theAtlantic Forest and forest remnants. A. Distribution of Hornschuchia, 105 points of occurrence. B. Species richness of Hornschuchia. C. Species abundance of Hornschuchia. D. Bioregions found by InfoMap Bioregions for Hornschuchia. Abbreviations: BA= Bahia; ES = Espírito Santo; MG = Minas Gerais; RJ= Rio de Janeiro." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6823787" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6823787/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="93">7A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6823780" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6823780" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6823780/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="92" startId="17.[189,231,1963,1989]" targetBox="[189,1395,1069,1924]" targetPageId="17">
<paragraph blockId="17.[189,1398,1963,2025]" pageId="17" pageNumber="92">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,263,1963,1989]" pageId="17" pageNumber="92">Fig. 5.</emphasis>
Geographical distribution of 
<taxonomicName authority="Mello-Silva &amp; D. M. Johnson" authorityName="Mello-Silva &amp; D. M. Johnson" box="[594,1253,1963,1989]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Annonaceae" genus="Hornschuchia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Magnoliales" pageId="17" pageNumber="92" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="mediterranea">
<emphasis box="[594,918,1963,1989]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="92">Hornschuchia mediterranea</emphasis>
Mello-Silva &amp; D.M.Johnson
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Nees" authorityName="Nees" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Annonaceae" genus="Hornschuchia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Magnoliales" pageId="17" pageNumber="92" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="myrtillus">
<emphasis box="[1263,1398,1963,1989]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="92">H. myrtillus</emphasis>
Nees
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Maas &amp; Setten." authorityName="Maas &amp; Setten." box="[305,620,1998,2025]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Annonaceae" genus="Hornschuchia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Magnoliales" pageId="17" pageNumber="92" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="obliqua">
<emphasis box="[305,430,1998,2024]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="92">H. obliqua</emphasis>
Maas &amp; Setten.
</taxonomicName>
Abbreviations: BA = Bahia; ES = Espírito Santo.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="18.[189,319,369,395]" box="[189,319,369,395]" pageId="18" pageNumber="93">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,319,369,395]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="18" pageNumber="93" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,319,369,395]" pageId="18" pageNumber="93">Phenology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[189,1036,417,443]" box="[189,1036,417,443]" pageId="18" pageNumber="93">Flowering from February to April and fruiting from February to August.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[189,587,483,510]" box="[189,587,483,510]" pageId="18" pageNumber="93">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,587,483,510]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="18" pageNumber="93" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,587,483,510]" pageId="18" pageNumber="93">Preliminary conservation status</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[189,803,532,558]" box="[189,803,532,558]" pageId="18" pageNumber="93">
Endangered, EN B2ab(iii) (
<bibRefCitation author="Mello-Silva R. &amp; Lopes J. C. &amp; Johnson D. M." box="[511,790,532,558]" pageId="18" pageNumber="93" pagination="285 - 290" refId="ref23257" refString="Mello-Silva R., Lopes J. C. &amp; Johnson D. M. 2021. The new inland Hornschuchia mediterranea (Annonaceae) from Bahia, Brazil. Phytotaxa 483: 285 - 290. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / phytotaxa. 483.3.8" type="journal article" year="2021">
Mello-Silva 
<emphasis box="[661,719,532,558]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="93">et al.</emphasis>
2021
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[189,259,599,625]" box="[189,259,599,625]" pageId="18" pageNumber="93">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,259,599,625]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="18" pageNumber="93" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,259,599,625]" pageId="18" pageNumber="93">Notes</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[189,1399,647,820]" pageId="18" pageNumber="93">
<taxonomicName box="[189,515,647,673]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Annonaceae" genus="Hornschuchia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Magnoliales" pageId="18" pageNumber="93" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="mediterranea">
<emphasis box="[189,515,647,673]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="93">Hornschuchia mediterranea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[658,824,647,673]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Annonaceae" genus="Hornschuchia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Magnoliales" pageId="18" pageNumber="93" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="mellosilvae">
<emphasis box="[658,824,647,673]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="93">H. mellosilvae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in its larger calyx and globose, rounded or conical floral bud (
<figureCitation box="[319,448,683,710]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="13.[189,232,1856,1882]" captionTargetBox="[249,1350,341,1797]" captionTargetId="figure-11@13.[205,1383,265,1818]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="Fig. 4. Morphological characters of some species of Hornschuchia Nees. A. H. citriodora D.M.Johnson, branch with flower (J. Kallunki 342, SPF). B–C. H. mediterranea Mello-Silva &amp; D.M.Johnson (W. Thomas 12313, NY). B. Floral bud. C. Flower. D. H. obliqua Maas &amp; Setten, branch with terminal ramified inflorescence (A.M. Carvalho 798, NY). E. H. santosii D.M.Johnson, monocarp (P. Fiaschi 1226, SPF). Drawing by Laura Montserrat." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6823778" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6823778/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="93">Fig. 4B–C</figureCitation>
). However, 
<taxonomicName box="[589,783,683,709]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Annonaceae" genus="Hornschuchia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Magnoliales" pageId="18" pageNumber="93" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="mediterranea">
<emphasis box="[589,783,683,709]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="93">H. mediterranea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has smaller petals (
<quantity box="[1017,1116,683,710]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.5" metricValueMax="9.0" metricValueMin="6.0" pageId="18" pageNumber="93" unit="mm" value="7.5" valueMax="9.0" valueMin="6.0">6–9 mm</quantity>
long vs 
<quantity box="[1217,1329,684,710]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.65" metricValueMax="2.4" metricValueMin="0.9" pageId="18" pageNumber="93" unit="mm" value="16.5" valueMax="24.0" valueMin="9.0">9–24 mm</quantity>
long) fewer stamens (3–6 vs 10), more carpels (5–8 vs 4) and globose to ellipsoid monocarps, 6–11 × 
<quantity box="[1295,1395,720,747]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" metricValueMax="9.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="18" pageNumber="93" unit="mm" value="6.0" valueMax="9.0" valueMin="3.0">3–9 mm</quantity>
, with rounded apex and densely covered in trichomes (vs obloid with acute apex, 20–24 × 
<quantity box="[1277,1394,757,784]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.05" metricValueMax="1.2" metricValueMin="0.9" pageId="18" pageNumber="93" unit="mm" value="10.5" valueMax="12.0" valueMin="9.0">9–12 mm</quantity>
, glabrous).
</paragraph>
